**Found the root cause!** In `resolveGatewayListenHosts`:

```js
async function resolveGatewayListenHosts(bindHost, opts) {
    if (bindHost !== "127.0.0.1") return [bindHost];
    if (process.platform === "win32") return [bindHost];
    if (await (opts?.canBindToHost ?? canBindToHost)("::1")) return [bindHost, "::1"];
    return [bindHost];
}
```

This is the actual source of the dual-stack listener. When `bindHost === "127.0.0.1"` (or even custom IPv4), the function checks if `::1` is also bindable and adds it to the list. So with `customBindHost="127.0.0.1"`, the bindHosts list becomes `["127.0.0.1", "::1"]`, and BOTH get bound.

Wait — the function only checks `if (bindHost !== "127.0.0.1") return [bindHost]`. So if the user sets `customBindHost="127.0.0.1"`, this returns `[bindHost]` (no ::1). So that's not the cause for custom mode.

